This happens because you are using deplorably bad exception handling.

```
try {
 stuff();
} catch (Exception e) {
  e.printStackTrace();
}
```

Is the equivalent of: If bad things happen, shrug and just keep doing the motions even though they are now pointless, like a clich&#233;d silly robot in an old cartoon. A person on a bike when the chain comes off that just madly pedals onwards, oblivious to the notion that the pedal no longer does anything.

The correct approach is obviously to handle it properly, if you can. For the vast majority of exceptions, there&#39;s nothing you can do about it. In that case, your method should throw it onwards (`void foo() throws SQLException`). If that too is not possible:

```
try {
  stuff();
} catch (Exception e) {
  throw new RuntimeException(&quot;uncaught&quot;, e);
}
```

What&#39;s happening here is that the connection fails, but your code just prints something and keeps going, resulting in `con` being `null`, causing _more_ errors. The result is a ton of errors, all of them irrelevant, except the first one.

What&#39;s the _actual_ problem? You didn&#39;t paste that part. But the exception will tell you. Probably wrong user/pass, or the mysql server isn&#39;t accepting TCP/IP based connections, or the mysql server isn&#39;t on, or any of a million other things it could be. That&#39;s why you want the error.

